<subsection>
    <title>Polynomial Functions</title>

    <definition>
        <title>Polynomial Function</title>

        <statement>
            <p>
                A <alert>polynomial function</alert> is a function of the form
                <me>
                    f(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}
                </me>
                where
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>a_{n}</m> is a real number called the <em>leading coefficient</em>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>n\ge 0</m> is a whole number called the <em>degree</em>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                The <em>domain</em> of a polynomial function is the set of <em>all real numbers</em>.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                The <em>graph</em> of a polynomial function is both <em>smooth</em> (no <em>sharp corners</em> or <em>cusps</em>) and <em>continuous</em> (no <em>gaps</em> or <em>holes</em>).
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>The Leading Coefficient Test (End Behavior)</title>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <em>Odd</em> degree polynomial functions
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Ends go toward <em>opposite</em> infinities
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <em>Even</em> degree polynomial functions
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Ends go toward <em>the same</em> infinity
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <em>Positive</em> leading coefficient
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                the right end goes toward <em>positive</em> infinity
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <em>Negative</em> leading coefficient
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                the right end goes toward <em>negative</em> infinity
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <image source="img/leadcoeff.png">
                    </image>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
        </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Turning Points</title>

        <p>
            If <m>f</m> is a polynomial function of <em>degree</em> <m>n</m>, then the graph of <m>f</m> has <em>at most</em> <m>n-1</m> <em>turning points</em>.
            (This also works in reverse: <m>n-1</m> <em>turning points</em> means the <em>degree is at least</em> <m>n</m>)
        </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Real Zeros and Multiplicity</title>

        <p>
            If <m>(x-r)^{m}</m> is a factor of a polynomial function <m>f</m> (where <m>m</m> is the <em>highest exponent</em> possible), then <m>r</m> is called a <em>real zero of multiplicity <m>m</m> of <m>f</m> </em>.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>r</m> has <em>odd</em> multiplicity, the graph will <em>cross</em> the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x=r</m>.
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The sign of <m>f(x)</m> <em>changes</em> from one side to the other.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>r</m> has <em>even</em> multiplicity, the graph will <em>bounce</em> the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x=r</m>.
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The sign of <m>f(x)</m> <em>does not change</em> from one side to the other.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            <alert>NOTE: Vocabulary</alert>  The following statements are equivalent for polynomial functions:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>r</m> is a real number for which <em> <m>f(r)=0</m> </em>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>r</m> is a <em>real zero</em> of the polynomial function <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>r</m> is a <em>root</em> of the polynomial function <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>r</m> is an <em> <m>x</m>-intercept</em> of the graph of <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>(x-r)</m> is a <em>factor</em> of the graph of <m>f</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>r</m> is a <em>real solution</em> of the equation <m>f(x)=0</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
        </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>SUMMARY: Steps for Graphing a Polynomial Function</title>

        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Check for <em>symmetry</em>.
                    (optional)
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Determine the <em>real zeros</em> of the function and their <em>multiplicities</em>.
                    Use this information to determine whether the graph <em>crosses</em> or <em>bounces</em> on the <m>x</m>-axis at each <m>x</m>-intercept.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Determine the <em>end behavior</em> as <m>x\rightarrow\infty</m> and as <m>x\rightarrow-\infty</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Find the <em> <m>y</m>-intercept</em> of the graph of the function by evaluating <m>f(0)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Find <em>additional points</em> between intercepts as needed.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw a <em>smooth curve</em> through the points to sketch the graph.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>(Sketching the graph of a polynomial from factored form)</em>  <m>f(x)=(x-2)(x+3)^{2}(x-5)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <p>
        </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Polynomial Inequalities</title>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find all solutions to the inequality <m>x^{4}+x^{3}-15x^{2}-3x+36&#x3C;0</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>
    </subsection>
